# How Big Is It?

Just like arrays, every string comes with a built-in `.length` property that tells you exactly how many characters are inside it (including spaces and punctuation!).

```javascript
let tweet = "Hello world!";

console.log(tweet.length); 
// Outputs: 12 (10 letters + 1 space + 1 exclamation)
```

If you want to build a feature like Twitter's 280-character limit, you would simply write an `if` statement checking if `tweet.length > 280`!

