## includes()

Often, we don't care *where* the word is; we just want a simple True/False answer if it exists.

Modern JavaScript gives us **`.includes()`**! It returns `true` if the text exists, and `false` if it doesn't.

```javascript
let url = "https://google.com";

if (url.includes("https://")) {
  console.log("This connection is secure! 🔒");
}
```

This is much cleaner than writing `if (url.indexOf() > -1)`!
